comments.body:
@AlexDeLarge thx for sharing. I think your criticism is valid, but I'm working on a large React-Redux based production-facing app and the amount of code duplication (sometimes literally copy-pasted, sometimes with very little differences) is just insane. 

Because the Redux action creators are modeled for containers instead of generic, parameterized API endpoints/ actions, we end up repeating ourselves way too often. 

We also have a large amount of "Reduxified" code in which Redux has no use whatsoever (no client-side caching needed, no state persistence). So I still think, even though it might not present sufficient evidence/ alternatives, there are important take-aways in the article.
